Snake pattern (8 options): The two-letter code tells you the starting corner and primary direction — "TL→H" means the snake starts at the top-left and runs horizontally first, snaking down row by row. "BR→V" starts at the bottom-right and snakes vertically, column by column. The IDs (2–49) are assigned in that traversal order, and the center is always fixed at 0.

Shift: Moves every room forward or backward through the snake sequence by that many steps, wrapping around. Use −1/+1 for fine control or −10/+10 to jump quickly. The shift is infinite in both directions.

Rotate: Spins the entire current grid layout 90° CW or CCW. This is applied on top of the shift, so you can combine any pattern + shift + rotation freely.

Ring rotations — three independent controls, one per ring. Outer (24 cells), Middle (16 cells), Inner (8 cells). Each rotates clockwise with positive steps, counter-clockwise with negative. The center stays fixed. Ring rotations stack on top of the snake shift and before the grid rotation.
Trip highlights — pick Trip 1 (yellow), Trip 2 (teal), or Trip 3 (red) from the panel, then click any cell on the grid to tag it. Click again to untag. A cell can belong to multiple trips at once (shown as a diagonal split). Highlights follow the room ID, not the grid position — so as you shift, rotate rings or rotate the whole grid, the colours move with the rooms. "None" mode lets you erase highlights from individual cells, and "Clear all" resets everything.

When you switch to Spiral↻, two new buttons appear below the shift controls:

▶ Push spiral forward — each click advances by one step, so 49 moves to top-left, then 48, then 47, etc. The label next to it always shows which room is currently sitting at top-left.
◀ Push back — reverses one step at a time.

The regular −1/+1 shift buttons still work too, so you can jump forward quickly and fine-tune from there.

The border pills at the bottom show you exactly which rooms are on each edge at any moment
